{"title_page": "Ghent Kangri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Ghent Kangri | other_name = Mount Ghent\n| photo = \n| photo_caption = \n| elevation_m = 7401\n| elevation_ref = <br /><small>[[List of highest mountains|Ranked 69th]]</small>\n| prominence_m = 1493\n| prominence_ref = \n| listing =\n| location = Siachen area of [[Ladakh]], disputed between [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]<ref name=\"bbc\">India is in ''de facto'' control of this region of Ladakh; the Indian claim is disputed by [[Pakistan]] which controls areas just a few miles to the west (west of the Actual Ground Position Line.) See e.g. ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/south_asia/03/kashmir_future/html/default.stm The Future of Kashmir]'' on the [[BBC]] website.</ref>\n| range = [[Saltoro Mountains]], [[Karakoram]]\n| map = Pakistan\n| map_caption = Gilgit baltistan\n| label_position = right\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|31|03|N|76|48|01|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| first_ascent = 1961 by Wolfgang Axt ([[Austria]]n)\n| easiest_route = West Ridge: glacier/snow climb\n}}\n\n'''Ghent Kangri''' (or '''Mount Ghent''', '''Ghaint I''') is a high peak near the north end of the [[Saltoro Mountains]], a subrange of the [[Karakoram]] [[mountain range|range]]. It is located west of the [[Siachen Glacier]] in an area under Indian control since 1984 on the [[Actual Ground Position Line]] with Pakistan.\n\nGhent Kangri was first climbed on 4 June 1961, by Wolfgang Axt, a member of an [[Austria]]n expedition led by Erich Waschak, via the West Ridge. He climbed solo above the high camp.\n\nAccording to the [http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index], there have been three subsequent ascents of the peak, in 1977, 1980, and 1984.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of highest mountains]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Jill Neate, ''High Asia: an illustrated history of the 7,000 metre peaks'', The Mountaineers, 1989.\n* Jerzy Wala, ''Orographical Sketch Map of the Karakoram'', Swiss Foundation for Alpine Research, 1990.\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Seven-thousanders of the Karakoram]]\n\n\n{{JammuKashmir-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Ghent Kangri | other_name = Mount Ghent\n| photo = \n| photo_caption = \n| elevation_m = 7401\n| elevation_ref = <br /><small>[[List of highest mountains|Ranked 69th]]</small>\n| prominence_m = 1493\n| prominence_ref = \n| listing =\n| location = Siachen area of [[Ladakh]], disputed between [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]<ref name=\"bbc\">India is in ''de facto'' control of this region of Ladakh; the Indian claim is disputed by [[Pakistan]] which controls areas just a few miles to the west (west of the Actual Ground Position Line.) See e.g. ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/south_asia/03/kashmir_future/html/default.stm The Future of Kashmir]'' on the [[BBC]] website.</ref>\n| range = [[Saltoro Mountains]], [[Karakoram]]\n| map = Tibetan Plateau\n| map_caption = Location in Ladakh\n| label_position = right\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|31|03|N|76|48|01|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| first_ascent = 1961 by Wolfgang Axt ([[Austria]]n)\n| easiest_route = West Ridge: glacier/snow climb\n}}\n\n'''Ghent Kangri''' (or '''Mount Ghent''', '''Ghaint I''') is a high peak near the north end of the [[Saltoro Mountains]], a subrange of the [[Karakoram]] [[mountain range|range]]. It is located west of the [[Siachen Glacier]] in an area under Indian control since 1984 on the [[Actual Ground Position Line]] with Pakistan.\n\nGhent Kangri was first climbed on 4 June 1961, by Wolfgang Axt, a member of an [[Austria]]n expedition led by Erich Waschak, via the West Ridge. He climbed solo above the high camp.\n\nAccording to the [http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index], there have been three subsequent ascents of the peak, in 1977, 1980, and 1984.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of highest mountains]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Jill Neate, ''High Asia: an illustrated history of the 7,000 metre peaks'', The Mountaineers, 1989.\n* Jerzy Wala, ''Orographical Sketch Map of the Karakoram'', Swiss Foundation for Alpine Research, 1990.\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Seven-thousanders of the Karakoram]]\n\n\n{{JammuKashmir-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "119.160.119.227", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghent_Kangri"}
