=Esparta |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Fanefjeld||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy UR 17]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean south of Iceland by {{GS|U-252||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of all 24 people aboard.<ref name=Fanefjeld>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/fanefjeld.html |title= D/S Fanefjeld |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Gala||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Benghazi]], [[Italian Libya|Libya]] by {{HMS|Thrasher|N37|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194204/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|SS|Henry Keswick||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The US Army requisitioned salvage tug caught fire from shelling, and was put ashore in [[Manila Bay]] off Corregidor Island. The [[Trose Emmett Donaldson|commanding officer]] was killed rowing for shore after his crew had been evacuated, though they were [[internment|interned]]. She was later salvaged, repaired and entered Japanese service as ''Keishu Maru''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gordon |first1=John |title=Fighting for MacArthur: the Navy and Marine Corps' Desperate Defense of the Philippines. |date=2017 |publisher=Naval Institute Press |isbn=9781612510620 |pages=218, 221 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XnDzMR47AXQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmm.org/pacific.html#anchor446443 |title=US ships lost in the Pacific during World War II |publisher=USMM.org |accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asiaticfleet.com/orbat.htm |title=United States Asiatic Fleet, order of battle, December, 1941 |publisher=Asiaticfleet.com |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Hermes|95|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Indian Ocean Raid|Operation C]]: The ''Hermes''-class [[aircraft carrier]] was sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] east of [[Ceylon]] by Japanese [[D3A]]1 dive bombers from {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Hiry\u016b||2}}, {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Sh\u014dkaku||2}}, and {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Zuikaku||2}} (all {{navy|Empire of Japan}}) with the loss of 307 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Hollyhock|K64|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Indian Ocean Raid|Operation C]]: The {{sclass2-|Flower|corvette}} was bombed and sunk in the Indian Ocean east of Ceylon by Japanese aircraft while rescuing survivors of {{SS|Athelstane|1918|2}} ({{Navy|United Kingdom|RFA}}). She sank in 30 to 45 seconds. 49 crewmen killed. Survivors rescued by Athelstane's lifeboats.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Lance|G87|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[L and M-class destroyer|L-class]] [[destroyer]] was bombed and sunk at [[Malta]]. She was declared a constructive total loss. refloated and towed to the U.K. for scrapping 1944.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/4463.html |title=HMS Lance (G87) of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Malchace||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|25|nmi|km}} off [[Cape Lookout (North Carolina)|Cape Lookout]], [[North Carolina]] ({{coord|34|28|N|75|56|W}}) by {{GS|U-160|1941|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 29 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Faja de Oro||2}} ({{flag|Brazil}}).<ref name=Malchace>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/1515.html |title=Malchace |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\