hts Award International Person's of Conscience|last=|first=|date=|website=http://whistleblowersummit.com/|publisher=Whistle Blower Summit for Civil & Human Rights|access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n;Martin Bossenbroek \n:2013 \u2014 Winner Libris History Prize for ''The Boer War''\n;[[Ivana Bodro\u017ei\u0107]] \n:2013 \u2014 Winner Prix Ulysse for ''Hotel Tito''<ref>https://www.actes-sud.fr/node/47253</ref>\n;[[Stephanie McMillan]]\n:2012 \u2014 Winner [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award]] in Cartoon for ''The Beginning of the American Fall'' and ''Code Green''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rfkhumanrights.org/who-we-are/awards/2012-journalism-award/|title=44th Annual RFK Journalism Awards (for 2011 Coverage)|last=|first=|date=|website=http://rfkhumanrights.org/|publisher=Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights|access-date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n;[[Linh Dinh]]\n:2011 \u2014 Winner Balcones Fiction Prize ''Love Like Hate''\n;[[Barry Gifford]]\n:2007 \u2014 Winner [[Christopher Isherwood]] Foundation Award for Fiction for ''Memories from a Sinking Ship''\n;[[Avner Mandelman]]\n:2005 \u2014 Winner I.J. Siegel Award for Jewish Fiction for Talking to the Enemy \n;[[Ralph Nader]]\n:2001 \u2014 Winner Firecracker Alternative Book Award for ''The Ralph Nader Reader''\n;[[Alan Dugan]]\n:2001 \u2014 Winner [[National Book Award for Poetry]] for ''Poems Seven''<ref>https://www.nationalbook.org/books/poems-seven-new-and-complete-poetry/</ref> \n;[[Jorge_Franco_(writer)|Jorge Franco]]\n:2000 \u2014 Winner Dashiell Hammett Prize for ''Rosario Tijeras''\n;[[Martin Winckler]] \n:1998 \u2014 Winner [[Prix_du_Livre_Inter|Prix du Livre]] for ''The Case of Dr. Sachs''\n;Sonia Rivera-Vald\u00e9s\n:1997 \u2014 Winner [[Casa de las Am\u00e9ricas]] for ''Las historias prohibidas de Marta Veneranda''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sevenstories.com/ Seven Stories Press official site]\n*[http://www.bookdepository.com/publisher/oftheweek/name/seven-stories-press/page/10 Book Depository article naming Seven Stories Independent Publisher of the Week]\n\n[[Category:Book publishing companies based in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Political book publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American independent publishing company}}\n{{Infobox publisher\n| name         = Seven Stories Press\n| image        = [[Image:SevenStoriesPressLogo.png]]\n| caption      =\n| parent       = \n| status       = \n| traded_as    =\n| predecessor  =\n| founded      = 1995\n| founder      = Dan Simon\n| successor    = \n| country      = United States\n| headquarters = [[New York City, New York]], [[United States]]\n| distribution = [[Penguin Random House]] Publisher Services (Global excluding UK)<br>Turnaround Publisher Services (UK)<ref>{{Cite web |title= Publishers Representatives {{!}} Publishers Distributors |publisher= Turnaround Publisher Services |accessdate = 2018-01-12 |url= https://www.turnaround-uk.com/publisher.html}}</ref>\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = [[Books]]\n| topics       = \n| genre        = \n| imprints     = Triangle Square, Siete Cuentos\n| revenue      = \n| owner        =\n| numemployees =\n| url          = [http://www.sevenstories.com/ sevenstories.com]\n}}\n\n'''Seven Stories Press''' is an independent [[United States|American]] [[publishing]] company. Based in [[New York City]], the company was founded by Dan Simon in 1995, after establishing [[Four Walls Eight Windows]] in 1984 as an imprint at [[Writers and Readers]], and then incorporating it as an independent company in 1986 together with then-partner John Oakes.<ref>{{cite web|title=CCCB/Participants Dan Simon|url=http://www.cccb.org/en/participants/file/dan-simon/24810|website=cccb.org/|publisher=Centre of Contemporary Culture of Barcelona (CCCB)|accessdate=26 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Pawprints|journal=Princeton Alumni Weekly|date=1 January 1987|volume=88|pages=17\u201318|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TBJbAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA54-IA13&lpg=PA54-IA13&dq=%22dan+simon%22+and+%22Four+Walls+Eight+Windows%22&source=bl&ots=GbJoj3h5-8&sig=k1MOjelw9npNkBFtVpnFeLbbsIU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjT8KWzhfnPAhWHuBQKHRtJDEgQ6AEIJDAB#v=onepage&q=dan%20simon&f=false|accessdate=26 October 2016|publisher=princeton alumni weekly|language=en}}</ref> Seven Stories was named for its seven founding authors: [[Annie Ernaux]], [[Gary Null]], the estate of [[Nelson Algren]], Project Censored, [[Octavia E. Butler]], [[Charley Rosen]], and [[Vassilis Vassilikos]].<ref>Witherell, Amanda. [http://www.newsreview.com/reno/content?oid=873313 Gaps in coverage.] ''Reno News & Review.'' 23 October 2008.</ref>\n\nSeven Stories Press is known for its mix of politics and literature, and for its children's books. As the publisher of a large catalogue of activist nonfiction and history from such authors as [[Noam Chomsky]], [[Angela Davis]], [[Greg Palast]] and [[Howard Zinn]], Seven Stories has had a major influence on public debate with books on foreign policy, the politics of prisons, and voter theft, among other topics.<ref>https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/72342-seven-stories-celebrates-20-years-of-books-on-social-justice.html</ref> Prominent titles include ''[[Dark Alliance]]'' by [[Gary Webb]], ''[[9-11_(Noam_Chomsky)|9/11]]'' by Noam Chomsky, ''[[A_Man_Without_a_Country|A Man Without a Country]]'' by [[Kurt Vonnegut]], and Octavia Butler's ''[[Parable_of_the_Sower_(novel)|Parable of the Sower]]'' and ''[[Parable_of_the_Talents_(novel)|Parable of the Talents]]''. [[Innosanto Nagara]]'s ''[[A is for Activist]]'', Howard Zinn\u2019s ''A Young People\u2019s History of the United States'', and Angela Davis's ''Are Prisons Obsolete?'', among many other titles, have educated communities of young people on key aspects of American history. Greg Palast's books have set the standard for raising awareness of vote theft in our elections. Seven Stories has for decades published the annual media censorship guide,\u00a0''Censored'',\u00a0by [[Project Censored]], and the ''World Report'' by [[Human Rights Watch]]. Seven Stories also publishes a wide range of literature, poetry, and translations in prose and poetry from [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]], [[German language|German]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], [[Russian language|Russian]], and [[Arabic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalbook.org/nbawinners_category.html#.WScPZRPysW0|title=NBA Winners by Category, 1950 - 2015, National Book Foundation, Presenter of the National Book Awards|author=|date=|website=nationalbook.org|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref><!--2001: Poems Seven: New and Complete Poetry by Alan Dugan = the National Book Award winning poetry-->\n\n== Imprints ==\n===Siete Cuentos Editorial===\nLaunched in 2000, Seven Stories\u2019 Spanish-language imprint, Siete Cuentos Editorial, publishes English-language activist nonfiction and history for Spanish-language readers. Siete Cuentos has published Spanish-language editions of ''[[Our Bodies, Ourselves]]'' (''Nuestros cuerpos, nuestras vidas'') and ''[[A People's History of the United States|A People\u2019s History of the United States]]'' (''La otra historia de los Estados Unidos''), among others. More recent Spanish translations include ''\u201868'' by [[Paco Ignacio Taibo II]], ''Columbus and Other Cannibals'' (''Col\u00f3n y otros can\u00edbales'') by [[Jack Forbes]], ''[[1491:_New_Revelations_of_the_Americas_Before_Columbus|1491]]'' (''Una nueva historia de la Am\u00e9ricas antes de Col\u00f3n'') by [[Charles C. Mann]], and ''A is for Activist'' (''A de Activista'') by Innosanto Nagara.\n\n===Triangle Square Books for Young Readers===\nLaunched in 2012, Triangle Square publishes progressive picture books, poetry collections, fiction, and nonfiction for preschool through young adult readers with the intent of promoting social justice, multicultural literacy, and environmental restoration. Triangle Square\u2019s bestselling titles include ''A is for Activist'' and ''Counting on Community'' by Innosanto Nagara, ''The Story of the Blue Planet'' by [[Andri Sn\u00e6r Magnason]], ''[[10,000 Dresses]]'' by [[Marcus Ewert]], and ''What Makes a Baby'' and ''Sex is a Funny Word'' by Cory Silverberg. More recent Triangle Square Titles include ''Where Do They Go?'' by [[Julia Alvarez]], ''The Wizard\u2019s Tears'' by [[Maxine Kumin]] and [[Anne Sexton]], and ''Arno and the Mini-Machine'' by Seymour Chwast. Several titles in Triangle Square\u2019s For Young People series, which adapts essential adult nonfiction titles for younger readers, have been adopted for middle-grade classes in school districts across the country, including Howard Zinn's ''A Young People's History of the United States'' and [[Ronald Takaki]]'s ''A Different Mirror for Young People''.<ref>https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-book-news/article/81209-adult-authors-dominate-triangle-square-s-fall-list.html</ref>\n\n===Seven Stories UK===\nIn 2016, Seven Stories UK was incorporated in England and is currently based in Liverpool. Seven Stories UK releases separate UK editions of literary titles, especially works in translation, and promotes Seven Stories Press titles with strong UK potential, such as feminist blogger Emma's ''The Mental Load'' and ''The Emotional Load'', and American playwright and novelist [[Kia Corthron]], author of ''[[The Castle Cross the Magnet Carter]]'', winner of the Center for Fiction First Novel prize in 2016.\n\n==Authors published by Seven Stories==\n===Fiction===\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n*Tatamkhulu Afrika\n*[[Nelson 